# No `any` Types

The `@typescript-eslint/no-explicit-any` ESLint rule is set to `error`. Never use `any` — it defeats TypeScript's type safety guarantees.

## Alternatives

**For test stubs**, cast to the real type using `as`:

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
expect(transform({ value: '16' } as any)).toBe('16.00dp');

// ✅ GOOD
import type { TransformedToken } from 'style-dictionary/types';
expect(transform({ value: '16' } as TransformedToken)).toBe('16.00dp');
```

**For unknown external data**, use `unknown` and narrow:

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
function process(data: any) { return data.value; }

// ✅ GOOD
function process(data: unknown) {
    if (typeof data === 'object' && data !== null && 'value' in data) {
        return (data as { value: string }).value;
    }
}
```

**For generic containers**, use a type parameter:

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
function identity(x: any) { return x; }

// ✅ GOOD
function identity<T>(x: T): T { return x; }
```
